a short analysis: the rename hooks trigger the file scan twice

long analysis:
1. hook \\oc\\files\\cache\\shared_updater calls getfileinfo which in turn scans the pdf (not the .part file) on the fly and inserts the new tupel into the filecache (insert)

2. hook \\oc\\files\\cache\\update tries to move() the file in the cache table by updating the .part file

unfortunately, the result would match the previously inserted tupel. so this fails with the integrity constraint violation.

i'm out of fuel for today ... n8

@mtgap @icewind1991 you are the authors of the two updaters. since the order of hook execution can vary (depending on the order of the connect calls) the oc\files\cache\shared_updater might scan files the oc\files\cache\updater wants to move. both triggered by a single rename. my feeling is that the oc\files\cache\updater must be executed first, to fix the cache mismatch. the oc\files\cache\shared_updater and also oca\\files_versions\\hooks should be executed afterwards. it's bad that a specific order is necessary but i don't see many alternatives.

webdav is not the only scenario where this might be necessary: refreshing the web ui during a web file upload will cause the file to show up with the wrong file size as well. that might cause the sync client to download a partially uploaded file. i think the cleanest approach would be to mark files being uploaded as 'in progress' in the file cache. i tried a hack where i kept the size at -1 for .part files which worked, but caused the web ui to scan the filesystem over and over again. i could change the js code to ignore .part files as well... but meh.

another approach might be to set the size to -2 (*hooray for magic numbers*) to mark .part files as uploads in progress. we could do that in a pre file_put_contents hook and clean it up after the upload. but this would very likely still require the oc\files\cache\updater to be executed first to not cause any other side effects. it would however allow us to show a file as being uploaded in more than the original web ui.

@mtgap @icewind1991 @karlitschek @schiesbn @deepdiver1975 @tanghus @bartv2 any ideas? i'm a little out of wits. but we should try to solve this one for good.
